\n  // solution = particular XOR (sum of selected null basis vectors)\n  // We want to minimize the Hamming weight.\n\n  // First half: enumerate all 2^half1 XOR combinations of nullBasis[0..half1-1]\n  // For each, compute the partial XOR pattern applied to `particular`\n  // Store: for each pattern, the minimum weight contribution and the assignment\n\n  // This is the \"closest vector\" problem. Let me use a simpler approach:\n  // We compute the XOR of the null space vectors with particular for all first-half combos,\n  // then for each second-half combo, find the best first-half combo.\n\n  // Key insight: solution = particular XOR delta, where delta = XOR of selected null basis vectors\n  // weight(solution) = popcount(particular XOR delta)\n  // We want to minimize this.\n\n  // Represent particular and null basis as bigints for efficient XOR\n  function toBigInt(arr: number[]): bigint {\n    let result = 0n;\n    for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {\n      if (arr[i]) result |= (1n << BigInt(i));\n    }\n    return result;\n  }\n\n  function popcount(x: bigint): number {\n    let count = 0;\n    while (x > 0n) {\n      x &= (x - 1n);\n      count++;\n    }\n    return count;\n  }\n\n  function toButtonArray(x: bigint, n: number): number[] {\n    const result: number[] = [];\n    for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {\n      if (x & (1n << BigInt(i))) result.push(i);\n    }\n    return result;\n  }\n\n  const particularBig = toBigInt(particular);\n  const nullBasisBig = nullBasis.map(toBigInt);\n\n  // Enumerate first half\n  const firstHalfMap = new Map<string, { delta: bigint; mask: number; weight: number }>();\n\n  // Actually, for meet-in-the-middle on closest vector, we can't easily use a hash map\n  // because we're trying to minimize Hamming weight, not find exact matches.\n\n  // Alternative approach: since we have up to 40 free variables, and meet-in-the-middle\n  // gives us 2^20 * 2^20 which is too much for pairwise comparison...\n\n  // Better approach: use the fact that with 40 buttons, the solution space is at most 2^40.\n  // We can use a branch-and-bound or greedy approach instead.\n\n  // Actually, for this problem size (up to 40 buttons, 40 lights), the rank is at most 40,\n  // so free vars = numButtons - rank. In the worst case with 40 buttons and 0 lights that matter,\n  // we'd have 40 free vars. But with 40 lights too, rank can be up to 40, giving 0 free vars.\n\n  // Typical case: free vars <= 20, handled by enum. For > 20, let's do meet-in-the-middle\n  // properly: enumerate both halves and for each second-half combo, check all first-half combos.\n  // 2^20 * 2^20 = 2^40 is too much. Instead, enumerate both halves (2^20 each = ~1M each)\n  // and for each second-half combo, iterate through first-half combos sorted by contribution.\n\n  // Simpler: just enumerate all 2^half1 first-half deltas, and all 2^half2 second-half deltas.\n  // Total solution delta = firstDelta XOR secondDelta.\n  // Solution = particular XOR firstDelta XOR secondDelta.\n  // Weight = popcount(particular XOR firstDelta XOR secondDelta).\n\n  // For each second-half delta, we want the first-half delta that minimizes\n  // popcount((particular XOR secondDelta) XOR firstDelta).\n\n  // This is the nearest neighbor problem in Hamming space, which is hard in general.\n  // But with ~1M points in 40 dimensions, we can try brute force:\n  // 1M * 1M = 1T operations, too slow.\n\n  // Better: for small dimension (40 bits), we can split the 40-bit string into chunks\n  // and use lookup tables. But this gets complex.\n\n  // Pragmatic approach: enumerate all first-half combos (~1M), store them.\n  // For each second-half combo (~1M), iterate all first-half combos and find minimum.\n  // This is 1M * 1M = 1T, too slow.\n\n  // Let's try a different approach: since we want minimum weight, iterate from weight 0 upward.\n  // For weight k, check if any combination of k free vars (toggled) gives a valid solution\n  // with exactly k button pr